{"title": "Ghostly Glide", "content": "The simplest trick in horror is to make something natural act in a way that isn't. Ghosts can usually fly, walk through walls, disappear, and so on. But one need not invoke the whole suite of supernatural effects to achieve unsettling ends. Sometimes, a more subtle approach can achieve truly disquieting effects.\n\nA Ghostly Glide is when a character gets around by less than ambulatory means. The trope is usually invoked in one of two ways. Sometimes, fluid movement gives a character the appearance of floating, meant to highlight the character's grace and beauty. More often, however, it creates an unsettling effect. In most cases, the floating is clearly a sign of supernatural influence.\n\nCompare Power Floats, which is when the floating is done as a show of power, rather than to disquiet, though the two can overlap. A good rule of thumb is if it looks like the director put the character on a skateboard and then pulled the character across the screen, that's a Ghostly Glide. If a menacing character hangs in midair, that's Power Floats. Can be paired with Marionette Motion if the character in question is under the control of others. Compare Flash Step.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GhostlyGlide", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/UnfinishedBusiness", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/MyLittlePonyEquestriaGirlsLegendOfEverfree", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/Slayers", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/Ulysses31", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/AvengersInfinityWar", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Beetlejuice", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/BigTroubleInLittleChina", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheBluesBrothers", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DeathBecomesHer", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DraculaDeadAndLovingIt", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HouseOnHauntedHill1959", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MarsAttacks", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MenInBlackII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/LordOfTheRings", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/HarryPotter", "/